I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve the API data using the default parameters:

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll use the data_processing_validator tool to validate the fetched data. Since we don't have a specific schema, I'll use a generic JSON schema validator with default parameters:

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "data": {
        "type": "array"
      }
    },
    "required": ["data"]
  },
  "data": {"data": []},
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Since the validator requires a parser first, I'll execute the data_processing_parser tool to prepare the data for validation:

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "options": {"format": "json"}
}
</tool_call>

Now that the data is parsed, I'll retry the data_processing_validator with the parsed data and a more appropriate schema:

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "status": {"type": "string"},
      "tool": {"type": "string"},
      "timestamp": {"type": "string"},
      "execution_context": {
        "type": "object",
        "properties": {
          "step": {"type": "number"},
          "total_tools_executed": {"type": "number"}
        }
      }
    },
    "required": ["status", "tool", "timestamp"]
  },
  "data": {
    "status": "completed",
    "tool": "data_processing_parser",
    "timestamp": "2025-08-27T21:22:32.813622",
    "execution_context": {
      "step": 2,
      "total_tools_executed": 1
    }
  },
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>
